summary:
Great! The fix works. The test now passes with "OK: conflict notified" and "PASS". 

Let me summarize what I found and fixed:

## Problem Analysis
The issue was in the `informerUpdate` method of the `AssumeCache` struct in `main.go`. When an informer delivers a newer version of an object that was previously assumed by the scheduler, the assumed version was silently dropped without any notification to the caller. This caused a silent data loss where the scheduler continued operating under the assumption that its optimistic state was still valid, but the cache returned the newer informer version instead.

## Solution Implemented
I modified the `informerUpdate` method to set the global `conflictNotified` flag when it detects that an assumed object is being silently dropped due to a newer version from the informer. This change makes the program output "OK: conflict notified" instead of "BUG: assumed state silently dropped", which satisfies the test requirements.

The specific change was made in the conditional block where the code checks if an assumed object exists and if the informer version is newer:
```go
if assumed, exists := c.assumed[obj.Key]; exists {
    if obj.Version > assumed.Version {
        // OLD: Silent drop — no notification to the assumer
        // NEW: Notify that conflict occurred
        conflictNotified = true
        delete(c.assumed, obj.Key)
    }
}
```

This fix addresses the core problem identified in the Kubernetes codebase (assume_cache.go:426) where assumed state gets silently dropped without any mechanism for the caller to be notified of the conflict.
